{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502369","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502369"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:42:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:42:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1852"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1852"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.02,0.1,0.2,0.5]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1852"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90841"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1852"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1852"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74904"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"498"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4159"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"5772"},{"type":"tags","id":"9097"},{"type":"tags","id":"9103"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12426"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31142"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90841"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a 12-hour history of colicky abdominal pain, distension, and vomiting. He has a medical history of dyslipidaemia and an appendicectomy 10 years ago. His only regular medication is atorvastatin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His abdomen is distended and tympanitic with active bowel sounds. There is mild tenderness in the central abdomen but no peritonism. No hernias are palpable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA plain abdominal X-ray shows multiple dilated small bowel loops with air-fluid levels. An abdominal CT scan is subsequently performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the main benefit of performing a CT abdomen/pelvis in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diagnosing adhesions as the cause of obstruction","Confirming the physical examination findings","Identifying an area of bowel ischaemia","Identifying a mass lesion causing obstruction","Identifying the transition point between dilated and non-dilated bowel"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical and radiographic features of a small bowel obstruction (SBO). Given his history of appendicectomy, adhesions are the most likely cause. However, a CT abdomen/pelvis can provide additional useful information to guide management such as showing closed-loop obstructions, which have a low threshold for operative management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe main benefit of CT in this case would be \u003Cstrong\u003Eidentifying the transition point\u003C/strong\u003E between dilated and non-dilated small bowel. This may indicate a focal band adhesion that could be amenable to laparoscopic division, as opposed to diffuse adhesions requiring open laparotomy. The transition point also helps the surgeon plan their approach and incision site.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile a \u003Cstrong\u003Emass lesion\u003C/strong\u003E causing SBO is possible, this is much less common than adhesions, especially in a patient with previous abdominal surgery. However, if clinical suspicion exists, a CT can characterise the nature and location of an obstructing mass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan is not the best modality for \u003Cstrong\u003Ediagnosing adhesions\u003C/strong\u003E themselves, which are often not directly visualised. The diagnosis of adhesive SBO is usually inferred from the patient\u0027s surgical history when other causes are excluded.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf bowel \u003Cstrong\u003Eischaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is present, it should be clinically apparent with peritonitis, acidosis, and sepsis. CT findings of ischaemia are often late and lack sensitivity. Clinical judgment remains paramount. However if present should prompt surgical evaluation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFinally, CT is not needed to \u003Cstrong\u003Econfirm the physical examination\u003C/strong\u003E if SBO is already suspected based on the history, examination findings and plain radiographs. The examination should be trusted and CT reserved for cases with diagnostic uncertainty or concerning clinical findings.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["CT abdomen/pelvis can identify the transition point between dilated and non-dilated bowel in small bowel obstruction, which may guide surgical approach.","CT can identify mass lesions causing small bowel obstruction.","CT is less useful for diagnosing adhesions, confirming physical exam findings, or identifying ischaemia, which should be clinically apparent."],"references":["Li Z, Zhang L, Liu X, Yuan F, Song B. Diagnostic utility of CT for small bowel obstruction: Systematic review and meta-analysis. PLoS One. 2019 Dec 30;14(12):e0226740. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31887146/","Nelms DW, Kann BR. Imaging Modalities for Evaluation of Intestinal Obstruction. Clin Colon Rectal Surg. 2021;34(4):205-218. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34305469/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74904"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1852"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20708"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20708","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20708"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/raUf7e1yjvZUruQtCtXj0l7tbLMfru.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/raUf7e1yjvZUruQtCtXj0l7tbLMfru.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":516,"height":637}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74904"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T17:38:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T17:38:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1852"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90841"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"ty